    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "19fa4688_a3105f7a",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 66,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-06-30T21:06:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I’m not sure if any other part of the system (like the linker) actually guarantees that the minimum address of a module is loaded from byte 0 of the file.\n\nLooking at https://android.googlesource.com/platform/bionic/+/72007ee68f507c0ab952a0b98888fc19473ba6f0/linker/linker_phdr.cpp, phdr_table_get_load_size() just computes the maximum minus minimum addresses in the preferred load area specified by PT_LOAD entries. No consideration is given to fileoff at this phase.\n\nPerhaps it’s worth testing with a weirdo module that maps fileoff 0 at somewhere higher than its base address. It should be possible to craft this with a linker script. If it turns out that Bionic’s loader and glibc both don’t support modules like that, then we don’t need to try to either, we can just error out if we detect it.",
      "revId": "ba3472105c0496ec7447e72c8ea1318c1dfe8674",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "16451098_61770277",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 66,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-07-01T17:41:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e I’m not sure if any other part of the system (like the linker) actually guarantees that the minimum address of a module is loaded from byte 0 of the file.\n\nThe spec says to use the lowest p_vaddr. http://www.sco.com/developers/gabi/latest/ch5.pheader.html#base_address.\n\nI’m still concerned that an ELF image might not have a PT_LOAD that covers byte 0 of the file, since this reader depends on starting there at the Ehdr. Still trying to figure that out…",
      "parentUuid": "19fa4688_a3105f7a",
      "revId": "ba3472105c0496ec7447e72c8ea1318c1dfe8674",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "bc2b88ce_fce4750c",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 66,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-07-01T23:31:11Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I modified this method to collect the whole range and added GetPreferredElfHeaderAddress for determining load bias.\n\nI\u0027m pretty sure the ELF header/program headers aren\u0027t required to be loaded into memory at all, but if they weren\u0027t loaded we wouldn\u0027t have gotten this far using ElfImageReader as it is since it presumably started at an Ehdr. If we do encounter modules that don\u0027t load their headers, we could still find symbol information using they dynamic array pointer in the link_map, but might need a different abstraction that collects various ELF things from memory, without expecting an actual ELF file image.",
      "parentUuid": "16451098_61770277",
      "revId": "ba3472105c0496ec7447e72c8ea1318c1dfe8674",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4f1d152a_09052598",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 67,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-06-30T21:06:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Other thoughts: ELF seems to support modules that load discontiguously (sparse), but at least the Bionic loader reserves the entire address space from lowest to highest possible address, including the portion that the file doesn’t care to map. So I guess we shouldn’t need to worry too much about reading anyone else’s data out of sparse “holes.” (ElfReader::ReserveAddressSpace()) The reservation is at PROT_NONE, so read attempts in there should at least fail. (ReserveAligned())\n\nFor glibc ld.so, _dl_map_segments() uses PROT_NONE too if has_holes is true for a module (elf/dl-map-segments.h).",
      "revId": "ba3472105c0496ec7447e72c8ea1318c1dfe8674",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "1788ba96_6f720fac",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 67,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-06-30T22:07:49Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e For glibc ld.so, _dl_map_segments() uses PROT_NONE too if has_holes is true for a module (elf/dl-map-segments.h).\n\nBut it looks like the kernel’s loader doesn’t do this, it leaves the holes unmapped. (fs/binfmt_elf.c elf_map()).",
      "parentUuid": "4f1d152a_09052598",
      "revId": "ba3472105c0496ec7447e72c8ea1318c1dfe8674",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "db04ff8b_2515ad10",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 68,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-06-30T21:06:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "And another thing: glibc ld.so looks like it’ll break if you try to feed it a module where the PT_LOAD entries, in sequence, don’t refer to increasing load addresses, or at least where the first and last PT_LOADs don’t refer to the first and last mapped segments in address order. (_dl_map_object_from_fd from elf/dl-load.c, handling of maxlength). Bionic looks like it might support it, though.",
      "revId": "ba3472105c0496ec7447e72c8ea1318c1dfe8674",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ef3e4e80_fb3d1f1c",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 68,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-06-30T22:07:49Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e And another thing: glibc ld.so looks like it’ll break if you try to feed it a module where the PT_LOAD entries, in sequence, don’t refer to increasing load addresses, or at least where the first and last PT_LOADs don’t refer to the first and last mapped segments in address order. (_dl_map_object_from_fd from elf/dl-load.c, handling of maxlength). Bionic looks like it might support it, though.\n\nThe kernel does the same thing as glibc. fs/binfmt_elf.c total_mapping_size().",
      "parentUuid": "db04ff8b_2515ad10",
      "revId": "ba3472105c0496ec7447e72c8ea1318c1dfe8674",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c2c5f0ff_c31afd5b",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 68,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-07-01T17:41:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e The kernel does the same thing as glibc. fs/binfmt_elf.c total_mapping_size().\n\nThe ELF spec says that PT_LOAD entries need to appear in ascending p_vaddr order. http://www.sco.com/developers/gabi/latest/ch5.pheader.html#p_type\n\nSo we probably don’t need to worry about this aspect, but we can add a check to make sure that modules we interpret adhere to this requirement, rather than just assuming that they do.",
      "parentUuid": "ef3e4e80_fb3d1f1c",
      "revId": "ba3472105c0496ec7447e72c8ea1318c1dfe8674",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "aedd822a_13a3bd1d",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 68,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-07-01T23:31:11Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I added a check on load ordering and range validity in VerifyLoadSegments(), called from Initialize().",
      "parentUuid": "c2c5f0ff_c31afd5b",
      "revId": "ba3472105c0496ec7447e72c8ea1318c1dfe8674",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ec6f72ad_d780e9ff",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 160,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-06-30T21:06:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "#elif defined(ARCH_CPU_BIG_ENDIAN)\n\nto make sure that the macros we expect are defined: no need for an #else #error then, because expected_encoding won’t exist and it’ll be a compile-time error.",
      "revId": "ba3472105c0496ec7447e72c8ea1318c1dfe8674",
