    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "b4ba0f83_13075e14",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 213,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-06-30T21:06:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "You’ve already read the the Elf*_Ehdr and the program headers by the time you reach this, but you weren’t able to verify that they were in the right range. Now that you’ve worked out the module’s base and end, you can do a quick check to make sure that the program headers were in range. No need to re-read them, but you can pretty easily figure out whether the Ehdr was in range (since you’re in the same scope), and maybe you can ask the ProgramHeaderTable what range it read from and make sure that it’s inside memory_’s range too.",
      "revId": "ba3472105c0496ec7447e72c8ea1318c1dfe8674",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "78b2313a_151ff6a2",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 213,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-07-01T23:31:11Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Done",
      "parentUuid": "b4ba0f83_13075e14",
      "revId": "ba3472105c0496ec7447e72c8ea1318c1dfe8674",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e0a50c80_be931e5a",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 266,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-06-30T21:06:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Shouldn’t load bias be applied to SHN_COMMON too? Ought to be able to test most of that.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 266,
        "startChar": 31,
        "endLine": 266,
        "endChar": 55
      },
      "revId": "ba3472105c0496ec7447e72c8ea1318c1dfe8674",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "0f659313_dfbc202f",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 266,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-07-01T23:31:11Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The description for SHN_COMMON is:\n\"The symbol labels a common block that has not yet been allocated. The symbol\u0027s value gives alignment constraints, similar to a section\u0027s sh_addralign member. The link editor will allocate the storage for the symbol at an address that is a multiple of st_value. The symbol\u0027s size tells how many bytes are required. Symbols with section index SHN_COMMON may appear only in relocatable objects.\"\n\nI interpreted that to mean that SHN_COMMON shouldn\u0027t appear in shared libraries/executables at all. (not totally sure on the intent behind \"relocatable objects\", but I suspect it means relocatable .o files). If it does appear in something we\u0027re reading, the value gives alignment, not an actual address.\n\nI wrote a test fortran module with a common block. Compiling to a relocatable .o includes a COMMON entry in the symbol table with value 0x10. If I turn that .o into a shared library the COMMON entry gets replaced by an entry with index 19 (the .bss section for this .so) and value 0x201040.\n\nAll that said, maybe it\u0027s better to reject symbols with SHN_COMMON entirely...",
      "parentUuid": "e0a50c80_be931e5a",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 266,
        "startChar": 31,
        "endLine": 266,
        "endChar": 55
      },
      "revId": "ba3472105c0496ec7447e72c8ea1318c1dfe8674",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "91d93509_1ebcebc9",
        "filename": "snapshot/linux/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 24
      },
      "lineNbr": 266,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-07-02T03:34:57Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e All that said, maybe it\u0027s better to reject symbols with SHN_COMMON entirely...\n\nAssuming that common symbols aren’t expected to survive all the way to linker output/loader input, that sounds like the right approach to me. Much better to not support it at all if it’s unexpected than to invent our own interpretation.",
      "parentUuid": "0f659313_dfbc202f",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 266,
        "startChar": 31,
        "endLine": 266,
        "endChar": 55
      },
